        <section>
            <div class="intro">
                <strong>Introduction:</strong><br>
                Nikhil Kamath was born on <strong>5 September 1986</strong> in Shimoga, Karnataka, and became India's
                youngest billionaire through his revolutionary fintech company Zerodha. He transformed from a high
                school dropout working in call centers to co-founding India's largest retail brokerage, democratizing
                stock market access for millions of young Indians.

                <br><br><strong>Family Background:</strong><br>
                His father, <strong>Raghuram (U.R.) Kamath</strong>, worked as an executive at Canara Bank, and his
                mother, <strong>Revathi Kamath</strong>, is a talented veena player and environmentalist who ran an
                event management company. The family belonged to the middle-class Konkani Brahmin community and
                frequently relocated due to his father's banking job transfers before settling in Bangalore.

                <br><br><strong>Interests and Early Life:</strong><br>
                His father's career as a Canara Bank executive exposed young Nikhil to the world of financial
                responsibility and disciplined middle-class values, shaping his analytical mindset toward money and
                markets. From a very young age, Nikhil showed signs of exceptional mathematical brilliance and
                entrepreneurial instincts, constantly questioning traditional educational approaches and seeking
                practical applications for his skills. He had a curious mind drawn to numbers, patterns, and
                risk-taking, preferring to learn through real-world experimentation rather than classroom theory. Nikhil
                read extensively about business, finance, and technology, eagerly absorbing knowledge about how markets
                functioned and how money could be made to work efficiently. Even as a teenager, he experimented with
                small entrepreneurial ventures like phone reselling, demonstrating an early appetite for business that
                worried his traditionally-minded parents. Nikhil's search for practical financial experience grew
                stronger as he became increasingly frustrated with formal education, eventually making the bold decision
                to drop out after 10th grade. The most pivotal change in his life came when he joined a call center at
                age 17, which provided him both steady income and the flexibility to teach himself stock trading during
                his spare time, laying the foundation for his later revolutionary impact on India's financial services
                industry.

                <br><br><strong>Entrepreneurial Path:</strong><br>
                Nikhil's journey from call center employee to billionaire entrepreneur exemplifies how technology and
                innovation can disrupt traditional industries. Along with his brother Nithin, he built Zerodha without
                any external funding, focusing entirely on customer value and technological excellence rather than
                traditional business metrics, ultimately democratizing stock market access for millions of Indians.
            </div>

